INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (530, '2012-05-16 19:55:24', 7, 90, '<p>So I was sitting in the bathroom when the theme song to Walker, Texas Ranger popped into my head.  The line “If you’re in Texas look behind you, because that’s where the ranger’s ;ing to be.”  It ;t me thinking if Walker <strong>does</strong> ever sneak up or appear behind a bad guy in the series, and I honestly can’t remember and have no idea how I would search for that.</p>\n\n<p>So, in keeping with the theme song for the show, did Walker ever actually sneak up <strong>behind</strong> a bad guy?</p>', 1302, 817, '2012-12-11 02:49:44', '2012-12-11 02:49:44', 'Did Walker ever show up behind the bad guy?', '<walker-texas-ranger>', '2012-07-14 19:55:24');
INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (531, '2012-05-16 20:40:46', 11, 3498, '<p>As Executive Producer Matthew Weiner asserts in this article, the character of Don Draper is based on the \"creative head\" of advertising agency Leo Burnett in the 1960s, Draper Daniels.</p>\n\n<p>What about the firm where the fictional character Don Draper plies his trade, Sterling Cooper Draper Price (formerly of Sterling Cooper)? Is there any pattern connecting accounts the firm has on the show and a real-life ad agency?</p>', 1444, 1693, '2012-05-16 20:56:47', '2012-10-10 06:17:32', 'In Mad Men, is the firm of Sterling Cooper Draper Price (or its earlier iteration, Sterling Cooper) based on a real advertising agency?', '<mad-men>', '2012-06-03 20:40:46');
