INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (1157, '2012-12-20 19:25:50', 3, 274, '<p>The ;lden drinking horn proved useful in the cave, but it did not look like Beowulf (from <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beowulf_%282007_film%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">the 2007 movie</a>) knew it would. Why did he bring it, especially since his sole purpose to visit that cave was to kill the witch?</p>', 970, 440, '2012-12-21 15:37:02', '2013-03-21 16:51:27', 'Why did Beowulf bring the prized gift to the cave?', '<plot-explanation><beowulf>', '2013-02-16 19:25:50');
INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (1158, '2012-12-20 20:01:00', 17, 1276, '<p>This thought recently occurred to me while reading up on theories for the finale.</p>\n\n<p>Season 7 had an overwhelming theme of love and what one would do in the name of love with all the storylines:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Dexter doing whatever it takes to protect Hannah from her father and Isaak.</li>\n<li>Isaak doing whatever it took in order to avenge Viktor, his lover.</li>\n<li>Quinn ;ing back to his dirty cop ways in order to protect his new found love, including shooting himself to protect her.</li>\n<li>LaGuerta using her past love for Doakes to risk her life and job proving his innocence</li>\n<li>Debra ;ing against everything she believes in as a cop in order to protect Dexter\'s true identity.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>It might be possible that this is the only season to incorporate this but do the other seasons do this in some capacity?</p>', 13, 1432, NULL, '2013-06-09 23:27:51', 'Does each season of Dexter have an overarching theme?', '<analysis><dexter>', '2013-01-14 20:01:00');
INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (1159, '2012-12-20 22:12:13', 4, 204, '<p>I\'m looking for an american movie or TV show with a scene where a kid (possibly 9-13 years) uses his computer to develop a simple game (similar to Space Invaders). In that game the player shoots at a picture of his school bully\'s or his sister\'s face (I can\'t remember which one exactly). The scene happens after he arrives home after school.</p>\n\n<p>The scene is not that relevant to the plot, but it\'s the one I want to watch. I\'m pretty sure I saw this more than 8 years a;, but I\'m pretty sure it is older, more than 12 years. </p>\n\n<p>In resume:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Around 1985 - 1999</li>\n<li>Prota;nists are kids</li>\n<li>There is a scene where the kid develop a game with the face or his bully or older sister</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Sorry if this is too vague... but it\'s what I can recall about it. If you know a movie or TV show with a similar scene I\'m interested in watching it!</p>', 1487, 1637, '2013-09-18 15:13:09', '2013-09-18 15:13:09', 'Kid develops a computer game in which he can shoot at the face of his bully', '<identify-this-movie><identify-this-tv-show><80s><90s>', '2013-01-29 22:12:13');
INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (1160, '2012-12-21 00:33:56', 24, 46745, '<p>Towards the end of the movie Life Of Pi, we are given a new vision of the events depicted in the story.\nThe writer that interviews the main character explains that the Zebra, Orang-Utan, Hyena, and Tiger from the main story represent the Buddhist Sailor, Pi\'s mother, the Cook, and Pi\'s dark (murderous) side.<br>\nIf we assume this logic applies to all the events between the sunk of the ship, and Pi\'s rescue on Mexico shores; there is an episode left unexplained. This is the part when Pi discovers an island made of floating trees, whose waters dissolve animals at night.  </p>\n\n<p>What could represent this event in the alternate vision of the story?<br>\nWhat could be the meaning of this short episode?  </p>\n\n<p>It is all the more disturbing since this is the most \"hard to believe\" part in the first version of Pi\'s story.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/kXDOp.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></p>', 1617, 705, '2013-05-14 22:48:14', '2013-11-03 17:25:24', 'What would be the equivalent of the carnivorous island?', '<analysis><life-of-pi>', '2013-01-31 00:33:56');
